WEBVTT

1
00:00:38.830 --> 00:00:44.860
<i>♪ Take me back
like a child to see</i>

2
00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:47.460
<i>♪ Faces lost in the memories</i>

3
00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:54.250
<i>♪ If I could only go back again</i>

4
00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:06.120
Stop it. Come on, get out of there.

5
00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:08.590
Stop it.

6
00:01:10.460 --> 00:01:11.520
Hey, hey!

7
00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:13.790
Get outta here. Get.

8
00:01:17.270 --> 00:01:19.030
Hey, fella.

9
00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:21.440
How you doing?

10
00:01:23.110 --> 00:01:25.410
He hurt you there?

11
00:01:30.150 --> 00:01:31.550
Oh, good dog.

12
00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:36.480
That's a good boy.

13
00:01:37.490 --> 00:01:40.050
That's a good dog.

14
00:01:42.590 --> 00:01:46.620
<i>It felt like forever</i>
<i>since I'd held a dog in my arms.</i>


15
00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:52.190
<i>No creature could live in my heart</i>
<i>like those dogs of mine so long ago.</i>


16
00:01:53.570 --> 00:01:57.630
<i>This place is far away</i>
<i>from the wilderness I came from.</i>


17
00:01:57.710 --> 00:02:00.610
<i>Forever, and a thousand miles away.</i>

18
00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:07.880
Here you go, boy.

19
00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:25.300
<i>I was a little boy growing up</i>
<i>deep in the Ozark mountains,</i>


20
00:02:25.370 --> 00:02:28.670
<i>with my mom and dad</i>
<i>and my two little sisters,</i>


21
00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:33.240
<i>and woods in all directions,</i>
<i>as far as the eye could see.</i>


22
00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:38.750
<i>My ma was part Cherokee,</i>

23
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:42.190
<i>and there was a legend in those parts</i>
<i>that a little Indian boy and girl</i>


24
00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:45.350
<i>got lost in a blizzard and died.</i>

25
00:02:45.420 --> 00:02:47.050
<i>When they found them in the spring,</i>

26
00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:49.960
<i>a beautiful red fern</i>
<i>had grown up between them.</i>


27
00:02:50.030 --> 00:02:52.730
<i>And that spot was sacred forever.</i>

28
00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:14.740
<i>-</i> Howdy.
- Howdy.


29
00:04:14.810 --> 00:04:16.780
<i>-</i> Morning.
- What can I do for you?


30
00:04:16.850 --> 00:04:19.220
<i>-</i> You Will Coleman?
- That's right.


31
00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:22.050
Well, this is Hud Bellington,
and I'm Ben Kyle.


32
00:04:22.120 --> 00:04:24.990
Good to meet you.
That's my wife, Jenny.


33
00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:26.490
- Howdy, ma'am.
- Howdy.


34
00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:28.490
And my daughter, Sarah.

35
00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:32.460
Alice, hiding behind the post.
And there's my son, Billy.


36
00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:34.260
We're up from Tulsa.

37
00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:36.270
Oh, really?
We got some kinfolk up there.


38
00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:38.960
We know that. Your uncle Fred's
the one that sent us out here.


39
00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:41.340
Says you got the finest
coon-hunting in the Ozarks.


40
00:04:41.410 --> 00:04:44.310
How about that? You hear that, Jenny?
Uncle Fred sent 'em down here.


41
00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:45.810
How's he doing?

42
00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:48.070
Feed and grain business
doing right good.


43
00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:50.620
Says he wants to sell,
move back East.


44
00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:54.020
Yeah, we heard about that.
We were hoping to...


45
00:04:54.090 --> 00:04:55.820
Hoping to make him an offer sometime.

46
00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:59.690
Boy, that sure would be
a fine thing for a family like yours.


47
00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:02.990
'Course, it'd be mighty tough
giving up country like this, too.


48
00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:05.830
- You'll stay for supper?
- Why, that's mighty kind of you, ma'am.


49
00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:08.030
Well, if we're going
to get any hunting done,


50
00:05:08.100 --> 00:05:09.970
we're going to
have to set up camp before dark.


51
00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:12.230
That is, of course,
if we have your permission.


52
00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:13.640
Oh, that'd be fine.

53
00:05:13.710 --> 00:05:15.770
There's a nice spot
just down the river,


54
00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:17.710
called Dripping Springs.

55
00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:19.570
Well, this road'll take you right to it.

56
00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:22.710
With hounds like these,
you're bound to tree a few.


57
00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:25.750
Well, they're the best
in Mr. Bellington's kennel.


58
00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:27.480
They're sure fine ones, mister.

59
00:05:27.550 --> 00:05:28.920
- They're champions.
- Yep.


60
00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:31.860
Won the coon-hunting competition
three years running.


61
00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:33.260
Is that right?

62
00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:36.560
Hey, you got any hounds
of your own, son?


63
00:05:37.460 --> 00:05:40.430
Well, ain't that a shame?
All this fine hunting...


64
00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:42.990
It's getting late, Kyle.
Maybe we ought to go.


65
00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:47.030
Sure thing, Mr. Bellington.
It's mighty nice meeting you folks.


66
00:05:47.110 --> 00:05:49.300
Yeah, y'all take care, now.

67
00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:53.840
I'm out back, son.

68
00:06:57.210 --> 00:06:59.200
Thank you, Billy.

69
00:07:02.550 --> 00:07:04.380
I was down at Grandpa's
store yesterday, and he said


70
00:07:04.450 --> 00:07:06.850
that old man Stanton's
collie's about to have pups.


71
00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:09.620
- And I'm sure he'd be glad to--
- Pa?


72
00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:12.520
I don't want no collie.

73
00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:13.850
I want hunting dogs.

74
00:07:13.930 --> 00:07:16.920
I know what you want, son.
But hunting dogs cost money.


75
00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:21.090
Right now there's a bluetick pup outside
Grandpa's store. It's going for $35.


76
00:07:21.170 --> 00:07:23.360
Can I go see him?

77
00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:25.840
Did you hear what I said, boy?
I said $35.


78
00:07:25.900 --> 00:07:29.310
Can I at least go look at him?
Please, Poppa?


79
00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:32.070
- Did you finish stacking that cordwood?
- Yes, sir.


80
00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:35.170
Well, I guess it won't hurt nothing.

81
00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:38.580
Be back by noon. You gotta
fix that fence down by the south end.


82
00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:39.980
OK.

83
00:07:40.420 --> 00:07:45.320
<i>Every town has its characters,</i>
<i>and every boy has his nemesis.</i>


84
00:07:45.390 --> 00:07:47.450
<i>Mine was the Pritchards.</i>

85
00:07:47.530 --> 00:07:50.360
<i>We didn't have no train</i>
<i>running through our neck of the woods,</i>


86
00:07:50.430 --> 00:07:51.790
<i>and no train tracks, neither.</i>

87
00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:56.800
<i>But if we did, the Pritchards would</i>
<i>definitely be on the other side of 'em.</i>


88
00:07:56.870 --> 00:08:01.140
I don't know. $35 is a lot
to pay for a dog like that.


89
00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:03.640
- He ain't worth more than 20, Pa.
- Hey, Billy. How you doing?


90
00:08:03.710 --> 00:08:05.940
Not even that much.

91
00:08:06.010 --> 00:08:12.750
Well, if you don't like the price, you better
talk to Chet Parker. It's his hound.


92
00:08:12.820 --> 00:08:15.580
I'm just trying to sell it for him.

93
00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:20.120
All right. We'll take it.

94
00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:23.090
It ain't no $35 dog.

95
00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:27.390
But I promised these boys a hound, I'm
gonna get 'em one. Even if it is a poor one.


96
00:08:27.470 --> 00:08:31.270
Now, there's five, 25, 35.

97
00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:34.070
Come on, boys.

98
00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:39.310
I sure seen better dogs in my day.

99
00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:43.410
It'll be hard,
but we'll make something out of him.


100
00:08:44.950 --> 00:08:48.440
Guess it's better than no dog at all.

101
00:08:53.890 --> 00:08:56.520
Well, that's a real shame.

102
00:08:56.590 --> 00:09:02.160
And, sure as I'm living, that's dog's gonna
end up being just as mean as they are.


103
00:09:02.230 --> 00:09:05.260
Bootleg money, that's for sure.

104
00:09:06.170 --> 00:09:08.440
Well...

105
00:09:08.510 --> 00:09:11.170
Oh, Billy.

106
00:09:11.240 --> 00:09:13.230
I wish I could have
bought him for you myself,


107
00:09:13.310 --> 00:09:17.150
but I ain't much
better off than your pa.

108
00:09:17.220 --> 00:09:19.180
Don't you worry, son.

109
00:09:19.250 --> 00:09:21.550
You'll have
your own hound before too long.


110
00:09:21.620 --> 00:09:25.950
I don't know, Grandpa. Sometimes
I think God don't want me to have any.


111
00:09:26.390 --> 00:09:31.350
Well, maybe that's 'cause
you ain't doing your fair share.


112
00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:34.400
- What do you mean?
- Ah, Billy.


113
00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:40.600
If God was a-minded to get you a dog,
that'd be easy as cutting lard.


114
00:09:40.670 --> 00:09:43.700
But then he'd be doing all the work.
That ain't good for your character.


115
00:09:43.780 --> 00:09:47.140
I don't want character. I want dogs.

116
00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:48.840
I know.

117
00:09:48.910 --> 00:09:51.780
And if you want dogs bad enough,
you're gonna have dogs.


118
00:09:51.850 --> 00:09:56.290
But if you want God's help,
you gotta meet Him halfways.


119
00:09:57.260 --> 00:10:02.020
- What does that mean?
- What, about meeting Him halfways?


120
00:10:02.090 --> 00:10:04.090
Well...

121
00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:10.100
Why don't you think about that? OK?

